  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Elite Includes Work Rights</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Thailand Elite does NOT include work permit. You cannot legally work for Thai employers or Thai-based clients. Remote work for non-Thai companies is tolerated but technically unauthorized. If you need to work legally in Thailand, consider LTR Visa or Business Visa instead.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Insurance Importance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Even if your visa doesn't require it (like Elite), health insurance is essential. Thai hospitals require payment/guarantee upfront. A serious illness without insurance can cost ฿1M+ out of pocket. Don't rely on "I'm healthy"—get covered before arrival.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring 90-Day Reporting</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Most Thai visas require 90-day reporting (notifying Immigration of your address). Fines for non-compliance. Elite members get simplified online reporting. LTR has 1-year reporting. Set calendar reminders—this catches many expats off guard.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">LTR Income Documentation Errors</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">LTR requires clear documentation of $80K+ income or $1M assets. Bank statements must be in English or certified translation. Income sources must be clear (employment contracts, dividend statements, etc.). Prepare thorough documentation before applying.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Property Ownership Rights</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Foreigners generally cannot own land in Thailand. You can own condos (up to 49% foreign quota per building) or lease land long-term. Don't assume your visa gives you property rights—research Thai property law carefully before buying.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

